From Steve Hayes Subject Re The arrogance of Christians In article A Melinda Hsu writes belief that their faith is total According to them their beliefs come from the Bible and the bible is the word of God and God is truth thus they know the This stance makes it difficult to discuss other faiths with them and my own hesitations about Christianity because they see no other Their way is the ' ' But I see their faith arising from a willful choice to believe a particular That choice is part faith and part reason but it seems to me a My discussions with some Christians remind me of schoolyard discussions when I was in grade school A kid would say All policemen are jerks I'd ask How do you know Because my daddy told me so How do you know you're daddy is right He says he's always right Well the argument usually stops right In the end aren't we all just kids groping for the truth If so do we have the authority to declare all other beliefs besides our own as false I find this argument very strange though not An analogy someone used a while back can perhaps illustrate Say for example there are people living on a volcanic island and a group of geologists determine that a volcano is They warn the people on the island that they are in danger and should A group of people on the island is given the task of warning others of the They believe the danger is real but others may Does that mean that the first group are NECESSARILY arrogant in warning others of the danger Does it mean that they are saying that their beliefs are correct and all others are false Some might indeed react to opposition with arrogance and behave in an arrogant manner but that is a personal It does not necessarily mean that they are all Steve Hayes Department of Missiology Editorial Department of South Africa Box Pretoria South Africa Internet